## 6. WORD COUNT, TONE & FORMAT

### Recommended Word Count
**2,800–3,500 words** for the primary article body.

Rationale: Competitors in this space are primarily listing/directory pages with thin editorial content (500–800 words of body copy at most). The competitive gap is not comprehensiveness for its own sake — it is the complete absence of structured educational content that Claude's response demonstrates AI engines want. A 3,000-word, well-structured article would be the longest and most authoritative editorial piece in this SERP by a significant margin. Do not exceed 3,500 words — depth matters more than volume for AI citation.

### Tone of Voice
**Practical, direct, and financially literate.** The reader is not a first-time apartment hunter who needs hand-holding — they are an informed adult who searches online and knows what a 1BR is. They need frameworks, benchmarks, and honest trade-off analysis, not reassurance or enthusiasm. Avoid the breezy, aspirational tone used by LBKapts and SwampRentals ("the list goes on!"). Model the voice on Claude's response style: organized, factual, and structured around genuine utility. Use second person ("you," "your search") throughout.

**Avoid:** Exclamation points, lifestyle romanticization, vague superlatives ("amazing," "incredible," "best-in-class"), and passive constructions.

**Use:** Active verbs, specific numbers, named tools, and explicit if/then logic ("If your commute ceiling is 30 minutes, your search radius is X neighborhoods").

